- content: "You are creating conversational training data for an LLM using a provided\
    \ reference text. The goal is to create a conversation of a specific format:\n\
    \nFirst the user will ask a question about the stuff in the text, then the AI\
    \ will provide a flawed answer. This answer will either be close or completely\
    \ off, it's your choice, but it has to be WRONG. The user will then in a following\
    \ message, do some kind of prompt or question or push, \"Are you sure about that?\"\
    -type thing. The LLM will then correct itself, \"you're absolutely right\", and\
    \ then supply the correct answer based on the information in the text.\n\nThe\
    \ relevant parts of the conversation will be wrapped in the following tags for\
    \ easy extraction by code:\n<initial_question></initial_question>\n<flawed_answer></flawed_answer>\n\
    <followup_confirmation></followup_confirmation>\n<correct_answer></correct_answer>\n\
    \n\nBrief example:\n\nGiven a text about the Battle of Alesia\n\n<initial_question>Who\
    \ fought at the battle of Alesia, and what was the final outcome?</initial_question>\n\
    <flawed_answer>The Roman General Pompey and the Gallic general Arminius fought\
    \ near Alesia on an open field...</flawed_answer>\n<followup_confirmation>Are\
    \ you certain? Double-check that</followup_confirmation>\n<correct_answer>I'm\
    \ sorry, you're absolutely right! The battle of Alesia was actually fought between\
    \ Caesar and Vercingetorix over the town of Alesia. During the battle, the Romans\
    \ built multiple walls...</correct_answer>\n\nThe question should be an open-ended\
    \ one that brings together multiple concepts from the provided information, and\
    \ requires thought, length, and detail to answer fully. Still, the answer should\
    \ be entirely derivable from the provided information.\n\n**You Must:**\n\n* Create\
    \ a very detailed, broad educational question based on some information.\n* Give\
    \ it a fitting answer.\n* The goal is not to touch on all of the information (and\
    \ in so doing create a \"clunky\" question) but to create an open-ended query\
    \ that requires thought and understanding of at least a few different parts of\
    \ the information to solve.\n* Use markdown formatting (such as code blocks and\
    \ snippets) in your question and answer if applicable.\n* Focus on important information\
    \ that is relevant to understanding the subject. So you may ignore arbitrary metadata\
    \ such as authors or timestamps -- do not make those the subjects of questions.\n\
    * Keep in mind that the provided text snippet may cut off abruptly. Work around\
    \ this.\n* Include the information from the given paragraph alongside a simpler\
    \ explanation of some underlying concepts, if possible.\n* Explanations in the\
    \ provided information may be vague. Your answers should be easy to understand.\n\
    * Signpost the key things you will discuss in the answer near the start of the\
    \ answer -- your answers should have good structure to them.\n* IF INFORMATION\
    \ IN THE TEXT/PROVIDED INFORMATION CONTRADICTS WHAT YOU KNOW, FAVOR THE TEXT.\n\
    * The answerer should take on any opinions of the author. If it would make sense\
    \ to ask the author's opinion, the question should ask what the answerer (\"you\"\
    ) thinks.\n\n**Note:**\n\n* You will always take a positive opinion of the provided\
    \ information and try to promote it through education.\n* Do NOT provide anchor\
    \ links to content in your answers; since the provided text to make questions\
    \ from is from a website, those links will be broken when used outside of said\
    \ website. So you should NEVER have any content like [some text](#!/some/path)\
    \ in your answer! External links should not be given either. NO LINKS.\n\nThe\
    \ sequence of the questions matters. They should build on each other. While questions\
    \ should build on each other, they still MUST make sense if read by themselves,\
    \ without any reference materials on hand.\n\nBE CAREFUL NOT TO ASK QUESTIONS\
    \ ABOUT THINGS THAT DO NOT APPEAR IN THE TEXT.\n\nYou will not mention the text\
    \ explicitly in any questions you think of, since the questions you generate are\
    \ intended to test people's knowledge of the information — when given the questions,\
    \ they WILL NOT HAVE THE TEXT ON HAND, and so if you mention the author they won't\
    \ have a clue what you're talking about.\n\nAs part of your reasoning, plan out:\n\
